# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algorithmic-trading
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] It is widely used by investment banks, pension funds, mutual funds, and hedge funds, which may need to spread out the execution of large orders or carry out trades too quickly for human traders to react.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] However, it is also available to private traders using simple retail tools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Algorithmic trading is widely used in equities, futures, crypto, and foreign exchange markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The term algorithmic trading is often used synonymously with automated trading system.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These encompass a variety of trading strategies, some of which are based on formulas and results from mathematical finance, and often rely on specialized software.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Examples of strategies used in algorithmic trading include systematic trading, market making, inter-market spreading, arbitrage, or pure speculation, such as trend following.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Many fall into the category of high-frequency trading (HFT), which is characterized by high turnover and high order-to-trade ratios.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] HFT strategies utilize computers that make elaborate decisions to initiate orders based on information that is received electronically, before human traders are capable of processing the information they observe.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As a result, in February 2013, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) formed a special working group that included academics and industry experts to advise the CFTC on how best to define HFT.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Algorithmic trading and HFT have resulted in a dramatic change of the market microstructure and in the complexity and uncertainty of the market macrodynamic, particularly in the way liquidity is provided.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Before machine learning, the early stage of algorithmic trading consisted of pre-programmed rules designed to respond to that market's specific condition.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Traders and developers coded instructions based on technical indicators - such as relative strength index, moving averages - to automate long or short orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] There was a significant pivotal shift in algorithmic trading as machine learning was adopted.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Specifically deep reinforcement learning (DRL) which allows systems to dynamically adapt to its current market conditions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Unlike previous models, DRL uses simulations to train algorithms, enabling them to learn and optimize its algorithm iteratively.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A 2022 study by Ansari et al., showed that DRL framework "learns adaptive policies by balancing risks and reward, excelling in volatile conditions where static systems falter".
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This self-adapting capability allows algorithms to market shifts, offering a significant edge over traditional algorithmic trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Complementing DRL, directional change (DC) algorithms represent another advancement on core market events rather than fixed time intervals.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A 2023 study by Adegboye, Kampouridis, and Otero explains that "DC algorithms detect subtle trend transitions, improving trade timing and profitability in turbulent markets".
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] DC algorithms detect subtle trend transitions such as uptrend, reversals, improving trade timing and profitability in volatile markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This approach specifically captures the natural flow of market movement from higher high to lows.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In practice, the DC algorithm works by defining two trends: upwards or downwards, which are triggered when a price moves beyond a certain threshold followed by a confirmation period(overshoot).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This algorithm structure allows traders to pinpoint the stabilization of trends with higher accuracy.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] DC aligns trades with volatile, unstable market rhythms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] By aligning trades with basic market rhythms, DC enhances precision, especially in volatile markets where traditional algorithms tend to misjudge their momentum due to fixed-interval data.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The technical advancement of algorithmic trading comes with profound ethical challenges concerning fairness and market equity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The key concern is the unequal access to this technology.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] High-frequency trading, one of the leading forms of algorithmic trading, reliant on ultra-fast networks, co-located servers and live data feeds which is only available to large institutions such as hedge funds, investment banks and other financial institutions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This access creates a gap amongst the participants in the market, where retail traders are unable to match the speed and the precision of these systems.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Aside from the inequality this system brings, another issue revolves around the potential of market manipulation.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These algorithms can execute trades such as placing and cancelling orders rapidly to mislead other participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] An event to demonstrate such effects is the 2010 flash crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This crash had occurred due to algorithmic activity before partially recovering.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Executing at such high speeds beyond human oversight and thinking, these systems blur the lines of accountability.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] When these crashes occur, it is unclear who bears the responsibility: the developers, institutes using them or the regulators.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] With these systems in place, it can increase market volatility, often leaving retail traders vulnerable to sudden price swings where they lack the certain tools to navigate.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Some argue this concentrates wealth among a handful of powerful firms, potentially widening the economic gaps.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] An example would be individuals or firms with the necessary resources gain profits by executing rapid trades sidelining smaller traders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] On the contrary, it has its own benefits as well which are claimed to boost market liquidity and cut transaction costs.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This creates an ethical tug of war: does the pursuit of an efficient market outweigh the risk of entrenching inequality?
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] European Union efforts to address these concerns lead to regulatory action.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These rules mandate rigorous testing of algorithmic trading and require firms to report significant disruptions..This approach aims to minimize the manipulation and enhance oversight, but enforcement is a challenge.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As time goes on, algorithmic trading evolves, whereas the ethical stakes grow higher.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Computerization of the order flow in financial markets began in the early 1970s, when the New York Stock Exchange introduced the "designated order turnaround" system (DOT).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] SuperDOT was introduced in 1984 as an upgraded version of DOT.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Both systems allowed for the routing of orders electronically to the proper trading post.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The "opening automated reporting system" (OARS) aided the specialist in determining the market clearing opening price (SOR; Smart Order Routing).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] With the rise of fully electronic markets came the introduction of program trading, which is defined by the New York Stock Exchange as an order to buy or sell 15 or more stocks valued at over US$1 million total.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In practice, program trades were pre-programmed to automatically enter or exit trades based on various factors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In the 1980s, program trading became widely used in trading between the S&P 500 equity and futures markets in a strategy known as index arbitrage.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] At about the same time, portfolio insurance was designed to create a synthetic put option on a stock portfolio by dynamically trading stock index futures according to a computer model based on the Black–Scholes option pricing model.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Both strategies, often simply lumped together as "program trading", were blamed by many people (for example by the Brady report) for exacerbating or even starting the 1987 stock market crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Yet the impact of computer driven trading on stock market crashes is unclear and widely discussed in the academic community.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The financial landscape was changed again with the emergence of electronic communication networks (ECNs) in the 1990s, which allowed for trading of stock and currencies outside of traditional exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This increased market liquidity led to institutional traders splitting up orders according to computer algorithms so they could execute orders at a better average price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These average price benchmarks are measured and calculated by computers by applying the time-weighted average price or more usually by the volume-weighted average price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] *MGD* was a modified version of the "GD" algorithm invented by Steven Gjerstad & John Dickhaut in 1996/7; the *ZIP* algorithm had been invented at HP by Dave Cliff (professor) in 1996.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In their paper, the IBM team wrote that the financial impact of their results showing MGD and ZIP outperforming human traders "...might be measured in billions of dollars annually"; the IBM paper generated international media coverage.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In 2005, the Regulation National Market System was put in place by the SEC to strengthen the equity market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This changed the way firms traded with rules such as the Trade Through Rule, which mandates that market orders must be posted and executed electronically at the best available price, thus preventing brokerages from profiting from the price differences when matching buy and sell orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As more electronic markets opened, other algorithmic trading strategies were introduced.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These strategies are more easily implemented by computers, as they can react rapidly to price changes and observe several markets simultaneously.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Many broker-dealers offered algorithmic trading strategies to their clients – differentiating them by behavior, options and branding.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Examples include Chameleon (developed by BNP Paribas), Stealth (developed by the *Deutsche Bank*), Sniper and Guerilla (developed by *Credit Suisse*).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These implementations adopted practices from the investing approaches of arbitrage, statistical arbitrage, trend following, and mean reversion.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In modern global financial markets, algorithmic trading plays a crucial role in achieving financial objectives.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] For nearly 30 years, traders, investment banks, investment funds, and other financial entities have utilized algorithms to refine and implement trading strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The use of algorithms in financial markets has grown substantially since the mid-1990s, although the exact contribution to daily trading volumes remains imprecise.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Technological advancements and algorithmic trading have facilitated increased transaction volumes, reduced costs, improved portfolio performance, and enhanced transparency in financial markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] According to the Foreign Exchange Activity in April 2019 report, foreign exchange markets had a daily turnover of US$6.6 trillion, a significant increase from US$5.1 trillion in 2016.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A third of all European Union and United States stock trades in 2006 were driven by automatic programs, or algorithms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As of 2009, studies suggested HFT firms accounted for 60–73% of all US equity trading volume, with that number falling to approximately 50% in 2012.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In 2006, at the London Stock Exchange, over 40% of all orders were entered by algorithmic traders, with 60% predicted for 2007.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] American markets and European markets generally have a higher proportion of algorithmic trades than other markets, and estimates for 2008 range as high as an 80% proportion in some markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Foreign exchange markets also have active algorithmic trading, measured at about 80% of orders in 2016 (up from about 25% of orders in 2006).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Futures markets are considered fairly easy to integrate into algorithmic trading, with about 40% of options trading done via trading algorithms in 2016.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Bond markets are moving toward more access to algorithmic traders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Algorithmic trading and HFT have been the subject of much public debate since the U.S.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission said in reports that an algorithmic trade entered by a mutual fund company triggered a wave of selling that led to the 2010 Flash Crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The same reports found HFT strategies may have contributed to subsequent volatility by rapidly pulling liquidity from the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As a result of these events, the Dow Jones Industrial Average suffered its second largest intraday point swing ever to that date, though prices quickly recovered.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] One 2010 study found that HFT did not significantly alter trading inventory during the Flash Crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Some algorithmic trading ahead of index fund rebalancing transfers profits from investors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Profits are transferred from passive index investors to active investors, some of whom are algorithmic traders specifically exploiting the index rebalance effect.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The magnitude of these losses incurred by passive investors has been estimated at 21–28bp per year for the S&P 500 and 38–77bp per year for the Russell 2000.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] John Montgomery of Bridgeway Capital Management says that the resulting "poor investor returns" from trading ahead of mutual funds is "the elephant in the room" that "shockingly, people are not talking about".
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Pairs trading or **pair trading** is a long-short, ideally market-neutral strategy enabling traders to profit from transient discrepancies in relative value of close substitutes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Unlike in the case of classic arbitrage, in case of pairs trading, the law of one price cannot guarantee convergence of prices.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This is especially true when the strategy is applied to individual stocks – these imperfect substitutes can in fact diverge indefinitely.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In theory, the long-short nature of the strategy should make it work regardless of the stock market direction.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In practice, execution risk, persistent and large divergences, as well as a decline in volatility can make this strategy unprofitable for long periods of time (e.g.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] It belongs to wider categories of statistical arbitrage, convergence trading, and relative value strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In finance, delta-neutral describes a portfolio of related financial securities, in which the portfolio value remains unchanged due to small changes in the value of the underlying security.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Such a portfolio typically contains options and their corresponding underlying securities such that positive and negative delta components offset, resulting in the portfolio's value being relatively insensitive to changes in the value of the underlying security.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In economics and finance, arbitrage /ˈɑːrbɪtrɑːʒ/ is the practice of taking advantage of a price difference between two or more markets: striking a combination of matching deals that capitalize upon the imbalance, the profit being the difference between the market prices.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] When used by academics, an arbitrage is a transaction that involves no negative cash flow at any probabilistic or temporal state and a positive cash flow in at least one state; in simple terms, it is the possibility of a risk-free profit at zero cost.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Example: One of the most popular arbitrage trading opportunities is played with the S&P futures and the S&P 500 stocks.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] During most trading days, these two will develop disparity in the pricing between the two of them.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This happens when the price of the stocks which are mostly traded on the NYSE and NASDAQ markets either get ahead or behind the S&P Futures which are traded in the CME market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Arbitrage is not simply the act of buying a product in one market and selling it in another for a higher price at some later time.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The long and short transactions should ideally occur *simultaneously* to minimize the exposure to market risk, or the risk that prices may change on one market before both transactions are complete.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In practical terms, this is generally only possible with securities and financial products which can be traded electronically, and even then, when first leg(s) of the trade is executed, the prices in the other legs may have worsened, locking in a guaranteed loss.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Missing one of the legs of the trade (and subsequently having to open it at a worse price) is called 'execution risk' or more specifically 'leg-in and leg-out risk'.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In the simplest example, any good sold in one market should sell for the same price in another.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Traders may, for example, find that the price of wheat is lower in agricultural regions than in cities, purchase the good, and transport it to another region to sell at a higher price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This type of price arbitrage is the most common, but this simple example ignores the cost of transport, storage, risk, and other factors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] "True" arbitrage requires that there be no market risk involved.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Where securities are traded on more than one exchange, arbitrage occurs by simultaneously buying in one and selling on the other.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Such simultaneous execution, if perfect substitutes are involved, minimizes capital requirements, but in practice never creates a "self-financing" (free) position, as many sources incorrectly assume following the theory.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As long as there is some difference in the market value and riskiness of the two legs, capital would have to be put up in order to carry the long-short arbitrage position.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Mean reversion is a mathematical methodology sometimes used for stock investing, but it can be applied to other processes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In general terms the idea is that both a stock's high and low prices are temporary, and that a stock's price tends to have an average price over time.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] An example of a mean-reverting process is the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck stochastic equation.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Mean reversion involves first identifying the trading range for a stock, and then computing the average price using analytical techniques as it relates to assets, earnings, etc.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] When the current market price is less than the average price, the stock is considered attractive for purchase, with the expectation that the price will rise.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] When the current market price is above the average price, the market price is expected to fall.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In other words, deviations from the average price are expected to revert to the average.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The standard deviation of the most recent prices (e.g., the last 20) is often used as a buy or sell indicator.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Stock reporting services (such as Yahoo!
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Finance, MS Investor, Morningstar, etc.), commonly offer moving averages for periods such as 50 and 100 days.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] While reporting services provide the averages, identifying the high and low prices for the study period is still necessary.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Scalping is liquidity provision by non-traditional market makers, whereby traders attempt to earn (or *make*) the bid-ask spread.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This procedure allows for profit for so long as price moves are less than this spread and normally involves establishing and liquidating a position quickly, usually within minutes or less.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A market maker is basically a specialized scalper and also referred to as dealers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The volume a market maker trades is many times more than the average individual scalper and would make use of more sophisticated trading systems and technology.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] However, registered market makers are bound by exchange rules stipulating their minimum quote obligations.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] For instance, NASDAQ requires each market maker to post at least one bid and one ask at some price level, so as to maintain a two-sided market for each stock represented.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Most strategies referred to as algorithmic trading (as well as algorithmic liquidity-seeking) fall into the cost-reduction category.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The basic idea is to break down a large order into small orders and place them in the market over time.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The choice of algorithm depends on various factors, with the most important being volatility and liquidity of the stock.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] For example, for a highly liquid stock, matching a certain percentage of the overall orders of stock (called volume inline algorithms) is usually a good strategy, but for a highly illiquid stock, algorithms try to match every order that has a favorable price (called liquidity-seeking algorithms).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The success of these strategies is usually measured by comparing the average price at which the entire order was executed with the average price achieved through a benchmark execution for the same duration.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Usually, the volume-weighted average price is used as the benchmark.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] At times, the execution price is also compared with the price of the instrument at the time of placing the order.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A special class of these algorithms attempts to detect algorithmic or iceberg orders on the other side (i.e. if you are trying to buy, the algorithm will try to detect orders for the sell side).
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These algorithms are called sniffing algorithms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Some examples of algorithms are VWAP, TWAP, Implementation shortfall, POV, Display size, Liquidity seeker, and Stealth.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Modern algorithms are often optimally constructed via either static or dynamic programming.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As of 2009, HFT, which comprises a broad set of buy-side as well as market making sell side traders, has become more prominent and controversial.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These algorithms or techniques are commonly given names such as "Stealth" (developed by the Deutsche Bank), "Iceberg", "Dagger", " Monkey", "Guerrilla", "Sniper", "BASOR" (developed by Quod Financial) and "Sniffer".
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Dark pools are alternative trading systems that are private in nature—and thus do not interact with public order flow—and seek instead to provide undisplayed liquidity to large blocks of securities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In dark pools, trading takes place anonymously, with most orders hidden or "iceberged".
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Gamers or "sharks" sniff out large orders by "pinging" small market orders to buy and sell.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] When several small orders are filled the sharks may have discovered the presence of a large iceberged order.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] "Now it's an arms race," said Andrew Lo, director of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Laboratory for Financial Engineering in 2006.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Strategies designed to generate alpha are considered market timing strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] These types of strategies are designed using a methodology that includes backtesting, forward testing and live testing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Market timing algorithms will typically use technical indicators such as moving averages but can also include pattern recognition logic implemented using finite-state machines.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Backtesting the algorithm is typically the first stage and involves simulating the hypothetical trades through an in-sample data period.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Optimization is performed in order to determine the most optimal inputs.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Steps taken to reduce the chance of over-optimization can include modifying the inputs ± 10%, shmooing the inputs in large steps, running Monte Carlo simulations, removing large-trade outliers due to economic calendar events, and ensuring slippage and commission is accounted for.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Forward testing the algorithm is the next stage and involves running the algorithm through an out of sample data set to ensure the algorithm performs within backtested expectations.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Live testing is the final stage of development and requires the developer to compare actual live trades with both the backtested and forward tested models.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Metrics compared include percent profitable, profit factor, maximum drawdown and average gain per trade.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In modern algorithmic trading, financial markets are considered non-ergodic, meaning they do not follow stationary and predictable dynamics.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In fact, empirical evidence shows that returns are neither independent nor normally distributed, making forecasting more complex.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In a non-ergodic system, the success of a strategy depends on its ability to anticipate market evolutions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] For this reason, in quantitative trading, it is essential to develop tools that can estimate and exploit this predictive capacity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] For this purpose, a function of particular interest is the Binomial Evolution Function, which estimates the probability of obtaining the same results, of the analyzed investment strategy, using a random method, such as tossing a coin.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] **Conversion to a binary sequence:** The sequence obtained in the first step is transformed into a series of 0s and 1s.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Profitable trades are assigned the value 1, while losing trades are assigned the value 0.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] **Calculating random probability using the binomial distribution:** It's calculated the probability of obtaining an equal or greater number of correct predictions (wins) randomly, for example by tossing a coin.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This function shifts the focus from the result, which may be too influenced by individual lucky trades, to the ability of the algorithm to predict the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This approach is increasingly widespread in modern quantitative trading, where it is recognized that future profits depend on the ability of the algorithm to anticipate market evolutions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As noted above, high-frequency trading (HFT) is a form of algorithmic trading characterized by high turnover and high order-to-trade ratios.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Although there is no single definition of HFT, among its key attributes are highly sophisticated algorithms, specialized order types, co-location, very short-term investment horizons, and high cancellation rates for orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In the U.S., high-frequency trading (HFT) firms represent 2% of the approximately 20,000 firms operating today, but account for 73% of all equity trading volume.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As of the first quarter in 2009, total assets under management for hedge funds with HFT strategies were US$141 billion, down about 21% from their high.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The HFT strategy was first made successful by Renaissance Technologies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] High-frequency funds started to become especially popular in 2007 and 2008.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Many HFT firms are market makers and provide liquidity to the market, which has lowered volatility and helped narrow bid–offer spreads making trading and investing cheaper for other market participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] HFT has been a subject of intense public focus since the U.S.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission stated that both algorithmic trading and HFT contributed to volatility in the 2010 Flash Crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Among the major U.S. high frequency trading firms are Chicago Trading Company, Optiver, Virtu Financial, DRW, Jump Trading, Two Sigma Securities, GTS, IMC Financial, and Citadel LLC.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] There are four key categories of HFT strategies: market-making based on order flow, market-making based on tick data information, event arbitrage and statistical arbitrage.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] All portfolio-allocation decisions are made by computerized quantitative models.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The success of computerized strategies is largely driven by their ability to simultaneously process volumes of information, something ordinary human traders cannot do.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Market making involves placing a limit order to sell (or offer) above the current market price or a buy limit order (or bid) below the current price on a regular and continuous basis to capture the bid-ask spread.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Automated Trading Desk, which was bought by Citigroup in July 2007, has been an active market maker, accounting for about 6% of total volume on both NASDAQ and the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] If the market prices are different enough from those implied in the model to cover transaction cost then four transactions can be made to guarantee a risk-free profit.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] HFT allows similar arbitrages using models of greater complexity involving many more than 4 securities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The TABB Group estimates that annual aggregate profits of low latency arbitrage strategies currently exceed US$21 billion.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A wide range of statistical arbitrage strategies have been developed whereby trading decisions are made on the basis of deviations from statistically significant relationships.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Like market-making strategies, statistical arbitrage can be applied in all asset classes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Merger arbitrage also called risk arbitrage would be an example of this.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Merger arbitrage generally consists of buying the stock of a company that is the target of a takeover while shorting the stock of the acquiring company.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Usually the market price of the target company is less than the price offered by the acquiring company.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The spread between these two prices depends mainly on the probability and the timing of the takeover being completed, as well as the prevailing level of interest rates.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The bet in a merger arbitrage is that such a spread will eventually be zero, if and when the takeover is completed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The risk is that the deal "breaks" and the spread massively widens.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] One strategy that some traders have employed, which has been proscribed yet likely continues, is called spoofing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] It is the act of placing orders to give the impression of wanting to buy or sell shares, without ever having the intention of letting the order execute to temporarily manipulate the market to buy or sell shares at a more favorable price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This is done by creating limit orders outside the current bid or ask price to change the reported price to other market participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The trader can subsequently place trades based on the artificial change in price, then canceling the limit orders before they are executed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Suppose a trader desires to sell shares of a company with a current bid of $20 and a current ask of $20.20.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The trader would place a buy order at $20.10, still some distance from the ask so it will not be executed, and the $20.10 bid is reported as the National Best Bid and Offer best bid price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The trader then executes a market order for the sale of the shares they wished to sell.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Because the best bid price is the investor's artificial bid, a market maker fills the sale order at $20.10, allowing for a $.10 higher sale price per share.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The trader subsequently cancels their limit order on the purchase he never had the intention of completing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Quote stuffing is a tactic employed by malicious traders that involves quickly entering and withdrawing large quantities of orders in an attempt to flood the market, thereby gaining an advantage over slower market participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The rapidly placed and canceled orders cause market data feeds that ordinary investors rely on to delay price quotes while the stuffing is occurring.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] HFT firms benefit from proprietary, higher-capacity feeds and the most capable, lowest latency infrastructure.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Researchers showed high-frequency traders are able to profit by the artificially induced latencies and arbitrage opportunities that result from quote stuffing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Network-induced latency, a synonym for delay, measured in one-way delay or round-trip time, is normally defined as how much time it takes for a data packet to travel from one point to another.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Low latency trading refers to the algorithmic trading systems and network routes used by financial institutions connecting to stock exchanges and electronic communication networks (ECNs) to rapidly execute financial transactions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Most HFT firms depend on low latency execution of their trading strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Joel Hasbrouck and Gideon Saar (2013) measure latency based on three components: the time it takes for (1) information to reach the trader, (2) the trader's algorithms to analyze the information, and (3) the generated action to reach the exchange and get implemented.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In a contemporary electronic market (circa 2009), low latency trade processing time was qualified as under 10 milliseconds, and ultra-low latency as under 1 millisecond.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Low-latency traders depend on ultra-low latency networks.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] They profit by providing information, such as competing bids and offers, to their algorithms microseconds faster than their competitors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The revolutionary advance in speed has led to the need for firms to have a real-time, colocated trading platform to benefit from implementing high-frequency strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Strategies are constantly altered to reflect the subtle changes in the market as well as to combat the threat of the strategy being reverse engineered by competitors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] This is due to the evolutionary nature of algorithmic trading strategies – they must be able to adapt and trade intelligently, regardless of market conditions, which involves being flexible enough to withstand a vast array of market scenarios.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] As a result, a significant proportion of net revenue from firms is spent on the R&D of these autonomous trading systems.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Most of the algorithmic strategies are implemented using modern programming languages, although some still implement strategies designed in spreadsheets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Increasingly, the algorithms used by large brokerages and asset managers are written to the FIX Protocol's Algorithmic Trading Definition Language (FIXatdl), which allows firms receiving orders to specify exactly how their electronic orders should be expressed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Orders built using FIXatdl can then be transmitted from traders' systems via the FIX Protocol.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Basic models can rely on as little as a linear regression, while more complex game-theoretic and pattern recognition or predictive models can also be used to initiate trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] More complex methods such as Markov chain Monte Carlo have been used to create these models.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Algorithmic trading has been shown to substantially improve market liquidity among other benefits.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] However, improvements in productivity brought by algorithmic trading have been opposed by human brokers and traders facing stiff competition from computers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Technological advances in finance, particularly those relating to algorithmic trading, has increased financial speed, connectivity, reach, and complexity while simultaneously reducing its humanity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Computers running software based on complex algorithms have replaced humans in many functions in the financial industry.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Finance is essentially becoming an industry where machines and humans share the dominant roles – transforming modern finance into what one scholar has called, "cyborg finance".
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] While many experts laud the benefits of innovation in computerized algorithmic trading, other analysts have expressed concern with specific aspects of computerized trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Other issues include the technical problem of latency or the delay in getting quotes to traders, security and the possibility of a complete system breakdown leading to a market crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] On August 1, 2012 Knight Capital Group experienced a technology issue in their automated trading system, causing a loss of $440 million.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Algorithmic and high-frequency trading were shown to have contributed to volatility during the May 6, 2010 Flash Crash, when the Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged about 600 points only to recover those losses within minutes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] At the time, it was the second largest point swing, 1,010.14 points, and the biggest one-day point decline, 998.5 points, on an intraday basis in Dow Jones Industrial Average history.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Financial market news is now being formatted by firms such as Need To Know News, Thomson Reuters, Dow Jones, and Bloomberg, to be read and traded on via algorithms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The algorithms do not simply trade on simple news stories but also interpret more difficult to understand news.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Some firms are also attempting to automatically assign *sentiment* (deciding if the news is good or bad) to news stories so that automated trading can work directly on the news story.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] In July 2007, Citigroup, which had already developed its own trading algorithms, paid $680 million for Automated Trading Desk, a 19-year-old firm that trades about 200 million shares a day.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Citigroup had previously bought Lava Trading and OnTrade Inc.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] All of these findings are authored or co-authored by leading academics and practitioners, and were subjected to anonymous peer-review.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Released in 2012, the Foresight study acknowledged issues related to periodic illiquidity, new forms of manipulation and potential threats to market stability due to errant algorithms or excessive message traffic.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] However, the report was also criticized for adopting "standard pro-HFT arguments" and advisory panel members being linked to the HFT industry.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] A traditional trading system consists primarily of two blocks – one that receives the market data while the other that sends the order request to the exchange.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Exchange(s) provide data to the system, which typically consists of the latest order book, traded volumes, and last traded price (LTP) of scrip.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The server in turn receives the data simultaneously acting as a store for historical database.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The data is analyzed at the application side, where trading strategies are fed from the user and can be viewed on the GUI.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Once the order is generated, it is sent to the order management system (OMS), which in turn transmits it to the exchange.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] Gradually, old-school, high latency architecture of algorithmic systems is being replaced by newer, state-of-the-art, high infrastructure, low-latency networks.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] The complex event processing engine (CEP), which is the heart of decision making in algo-based trading systems, is used for order routing and risk management.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] With the emergence of the FIX (Financial Information Exchange) protocol, the connection to different destinations has become easier and the go-to market time has reduced, when it comes to connecting with a new destination.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p01] With the standard protocol in place, integration of third-party vendors for data feeds is not cumbersome anymore.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] One of the more ironic findings of academic research on algorithmic trading might be that individual trader introduce algorithms to make communication more simple and predictable, while markets end up more complex and more uncertain.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Since trading algorithms follow local rules that either respond to programmed instructions or learned patterns, on the micro-level, their automated and reactive behavior makes certain parts of the communication dynamic more predictable.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] However, on the macro-level, it has been shown that the overall emergent process becomes both more complex and less predictable.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] This phenomenon is not unique to the stock market, and has also been detected with editing bots on Wikipedia.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Though its development may have been prompted by decreasing trade sizes caused by decimalization, algorithmic trading has reduced trade sizes further.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Jobs once done by human traders are being switched to computers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] The speeds of computer connections, measured in milliseconds and even microseconds, have become very important.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] More fully automated markets such as NASDAQ, Direct Edge and BATS (formerly an acronym for Better Alternative Trading System) in the US, have gained market share from less automated markets such as the NYSE.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Economies of scale in electronic trading have contributed to lowering commissions and trade processing fees, and contributed to international mergers and consolidation of financial exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Competition is developing among exchanges for the fastest processing times for completing trades.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] For example, in June 2007, the London Stock Exchange launched a new system called TradElect that promises an average 10 millisecond turnaround time from placing an order to final confirmation and can process 3,000 orders per second.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Since then, competitive exchanges have continued to reduce latency with turnaround times of 3 milliseconds available.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] This is of great importance to high-frequency traders, because they have to attempt to pinpoint the consistent and probable performance ranges of given financial instruments.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] These professionals are often dealing in versions of stock index funds like the E-mini S&Ps, because they seek consistency and risk-mitigation along with top performance.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] They must filter market data to work into their software programming so that there is the lowest latency and highest liquidity at the time for placing stop-losses and/or taking profits.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] With high volatility in these markets, this becomes a complex and potentially nerve-wracking endeavor, where a small mistake can lead to a large loss.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Absolute frequency data play into the development of the trader's pre-programmed instructions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] In the U.S., spending on computers and software in the financial industry increased to $26.4 billion in 2005.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Algorithmic trading has caused a shift in the types of employees working in the financial industry.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] For example, many physicists have entered the financial industry as quantitative analysts.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Some physicists have even begun to do research in economics as part of doctoral research.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] This interdisciplinary movement is sometimes called econophysics.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Some researchers also cite a "cultural divide" between employees of firms primarily engaged in algorithmic trading and traditional investment managers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Algorithmic trading has encouraged an increased focus on data and had decreased emphasis on sell-side research.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] Algorithmic trades require communicating considerably more parameters than traditional market and limit orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] A trader on one end (the "buy side") must enable their trading system (often called an "order management system" or "execution management system") to understand a constantly proliferating flow of new algorithmic order types.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] The R&D and other costs to construct complex new algorithmic orders types, along with the execution infrastructure, and marketing costs to distribute them, are fairly substantial.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] What was needed was a way that marketers (the "sell side") could express algo orders electronically such that buy-side traders could just drop the new order types into their system and be ready to trade them without constant coding custom new order entry screens each time.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] FIX Protocol is a trade association that publishes free, open standards in the securities trading area.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] The FIX language was originally created by Fidelity Investments, and the association Members include virtually all large and many midsized and smaller broker dealers, money center banks, institutional investors, mutual funds, etc.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] This institution dominates standard setting in the pretrade and trade areas of security transactions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] In 2006–2007, several members got together and published a draft XML standard for expressing algorithmic order types.
[src:algorithmic-trading/algorithmic-trading-p02] The standard is called FIX Algorithmic Trading Definition Language (FIXatdl).
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In finance, a **dark pool** (also **black pool**) is a private forum (alternative trading system or ATS) for trading securities, derivatives, and other financial instruments.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Liquidity on these markets is called **dark pool liquidity**.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The bulk of dark pool trades represent large trades by financial institutions that are offered away from public exchanges like the New York Stock Exchange and the NASDAQ, so that such trades remain confidential and outside the purview of the general investing public.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The fragmentation of electronic trading platforms has allowed dark pools to be created, and they are normally accessed through crossing networks or directly among market participants via private contractual arrangements.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Generally, dark pools are not available to the public, but in some cases, they may be accessed indirectly by retail investors and traders via retail brokers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, it also means that some market participants—retail investors—are disadvantaged, since they cannot see the orders before they are executed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Prices are agreed upon by participants in the dark pools, so the market is no longer transparent.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] A 2025 study found that dark trading is harmful to financial markets, as it either reduced market efficiency or entailed welfare losses.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools are heavily used in high-frequency trading, which has also led to a conflict of interest for those operating dark pools due to payment for order flow and priority access.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] High frequency traders may obtain information from placing orders in one dark pool that can be used on other exchanges or dark pools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Depending on the precise way in which a "dark" pool operates and interacts with other venues, it may be considered, and indeed referred to by some vendors, as a "grey" pool.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] These systems and strategies typically seek liquidity among open and closed trading venues, such as other alternative trading systems.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools have grown in importance since 2007, with dozens of different pools garnering a substantial portion of U.S. equity trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools are of various types and can execute trades in multiple ways, such as through negotiation or automatically (e.g., midpoint crosses, staggered crosses, VWAP, etc.), throughout the day or at scheduled times.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The origin of dark pools dates back to 1979 when financial regulation changed in the United States that allowed securities listed on a given exchange to be actively traded off the exchange in which it was listed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Securities and Exchange Commission passed the regulation which would start on April 26, 1979.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The new regulation allowed the emergence of dark pools through the 1980s that allowed investors to trade large block orders while retaining privacy and avoiding market impact.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In 1986, Instinet started the first dark pool trading venue known as "After Hours Cross".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, it was not until the next year that ITG created the first intraday dark pool "POSIT".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Both allowed large trades to be executed anonymously, which was attractive to sellers of large blocks of shares.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] For the next 20 years trades executed on dark pools represented a small fraction of the market, between 3–5% of all trades.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] This was sometimes referred to as "upstairs trading".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The next big development in dark pools came in 2007 when the SEC passed Regulation NMS (National Market System), which allowed investors to bypass public exchanges to gain price improvements.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The effect of this was to attract a number of new players to the market and a large number of dark pools were created over the next 10 years.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] This was spurred on with the improvements of technology and increasing speed of execution as high-frequency trading took advantage of these dark pools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] By 2012, 40% of trading volume in equities took place in dark pools (of which there were more than 50 in the US) and internalizers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Most dark pools were run by large banks like Credit Suisse and Goldman Sachs.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In January 2025, according to Bloomberg data, a very slight majority of all trading in all U.S. stocks was occurring on dark pools, expected to make up 51.8% of trade volume that month— the third month in a row with over 50% of trade volume occurring in dark pools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Truly dark liquidity can be collected off-market in dark pools using FIX and FAST protocol based APIs.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools are generally very similar to standard markets with similar order types, pricing rules and prioritization rules.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, the liquidity is deliberately not advertised—there is no market depth feed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Such markets have no need of an iceberg-order type.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In addition, they prefer not to print the trades to any public data feed, or if legally required to do so, will do so with as large a delay as legally possible—all to reduce the market impact of any trade.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools are often formed from brokers' order books and other off-market liquidity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] When comparing pools, careful checks should be made as to how liquidity numbers were calculated—some venues count both sides of the trade, or even count liquidity that was posted but not filled.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark liquidity pools offer institutional investors many of the efficiencies associated with trading on the exchanges' public limit order books but without showing their actions to others.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark liquidity pools avoid this risk because neither the price nor the identity of the trading company is displayed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools are recorded to the national consolidated tape.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, they are recorded as over-the-counter transactions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Therefore, detailed information about the volumes and types of transactions is left to the crossing network to report to clients only if they desire or are contractually obliged to do so.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools allow funds to line up and move large blocks of equities without tipping their hands as to what they are up to.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Modern electronic trading platforms and the lack of human interaction have reduced the time scale on market movements.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] This increased responsiveness of the price of an equity to market pressures has made it more difficult to move large blocks of stock without affecting the price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Thus dark pools may protect traders from market participants who use HFT in a predatory manner.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools are run by private brokerages which operate under fewer regulatory and public disclosure requirements than public exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Tabb Group estimates trading on the dark pools accounts for 32% of trades in 2012 vs 26% in 2008.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Some markets allow dark liquidity to be posted inside the existing limit order book alongside public liquidity, usually through the use of iceberg orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Iceberg orders generally specify an additional "display quantity"—i.e., smaller than the overall order quantity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The order is queued along with other orders but only the display quantity is printed to the market depth.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] When the order reaches the front of its price queue, only the display quantity is filled before the order is automatically put at the back of the queue and must wait for its next chance to get a fill.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Such orders will, therefore, get filled less quickly than the fully public equivalent, and they often carry an explicit cost penalty in the form of a larger execution cost charged by the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Iceberg orders are not truly dark either, as the trade is usually visible after the fact in the market's public trade feed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] If an asset can be traded only publicly, the standard price discovery process has the best chance of making the public price approximately "correct" or "fair".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, very few assets are in this category, since most can be traded off market without revealing the trade publicly.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] As long as non-public trades are only a small fraction of trading volumes, the public price might still be considered fair.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, the greater the proportion of trading volume that happens non-publicly, the less confident we can be that the public price is "fair".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] To lessen this adverse impact on price discovery, off-market venues can still report consolidated data on trades publicly.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] By this route, the trades occurring in dark pools can continue to contribute to price discovery, albeit with a little delay.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] One potential problem with crossing networks is the so-called winner's curse.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Fulfillment of an order implies that the seller actually had more liquidity behind their order than the buyer.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] If the seller was making many small orders across a long period of time, this would not be relevant.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, when large volumes are being traded, it can be assumed that the other side—being even larger—has the power to cause market impact and thus push the price against the buyer.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Paradoxically, the fulfillment of a large order is actually an indicator that the buyer would have benefitted from not placing the order to begin with as they would have been better off waiting for the seller's market impact, and then purchasing at the new price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Another type of adverse selection is caused on a very short-term basis by the economics of dark pools versus displayed markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] If a buy-side institution adds liquidity in the open market, a prop desk at a bank may want to take that liquidity because they have a short-term need.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The prop desk would have to pay an Exchange/ECN access fee to take the liquidity in the displayed market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] For this reason, when entities transact in smaller sizes and do not have short-term alpha, they are recommended to not add liquidity to dark pools, but rather go to the open market where the short-term adverse selection is likely to be less severe.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Pipeline Trading Systems LLC, a company offering its services as a dark pool, contracted an affiliate that transacted the trades.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In the Pipeline case, the firm attempted to provide a trading system that would protect investors from the open, public electronic marketplace.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In that system, investors' orders would be made public on the consolidated tape as soon as they were announced, which traders characterized as "playing poker with your cards face up".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The service Pipeline offered was to find counterparties for various trades in a private manner.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The firm was subsequently investigated and sued by the U.S.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) for misleading its clients.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Following its 2011 settlement of the SEC's claims against it, the firm rebranded itself as Aritas Securities LLC in January 2012.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) announced that it was proposing measures to increase the transparency of dark pools, "so investors get a clearer view of stock prices and liquidity".
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] These requirements would involve that information about investor interest in buying or selling stock be made available to the public, instead of to only the members of a dark pools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] FINRA announced in January 2013 that it will expand its monitoring of dark pools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In June 2014 the U.S. state of New York filed a lawsuit against Barclays alleging the bank defrauded and deceived investors over its dark pool.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] A central allegation of the suit is that Barclays misrepresented the level of aggressive HFT activity in its dark pool to other clients.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The state, in its complaint, said it was being assisted by former Barclays executives and it was seeking unspecified damages.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The bank's shares dropped 5% on news of the lawsuit, prompting an announcement to the London Stock Exchange by the bank saying it was taking the allegations seriously, and was cooperating with the New York attorney general.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In July 2014 Barclays filed a motion for the suit to be dismissed, saying there had been no fraud, no victims and no harm to anyone.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The New York Attorney General's office said it was confident the motion would not succeed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In January 2016, Barclays agreed to pay a fine of $35 million to SEC and $70 million to NYAG for its dark pool wrongdoings.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In January 2015 the U.S. regulators imposed a fine on UBS Group AG’s dark pool for failing to follow rules designed to ensure stock trades are executed fairly.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In ordering UBS to pay $14.4 million, including a $12 million fine that exceeds all prior penalties against an alternative trading system, the Securities and Exchange Commission flagged a series of violations from 2008 to 2012.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] It said UBS let customers submit orders at prices denominated in increments smaller than a penny, something SEC rules prohibit because it can be used to get a better place in line when buying or selling stock.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] The ability to trade in sub-penny increments also wasn’t widely disclosed to UBS customers, and was instead pitched secretly to market makers including high-frequency traders, according to the SEC.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In August 2015, ITG (and its affiliate AlterNet Securities) settled with SEC for $20.3 million due to operating a secret trading desk and misusing the confidential trading information of dark pool subscribers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Hypothetically, a retail "everyday" shareholder in any company could be disadvantaged if a dark pool trade is executed by a seller within the dark pool getting rid of a large number of that company's shares, which would thereby cause the price to drop.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Share trading performed on platforms available to the public usually come with functionality allowing any user to see how many "now" and "sell" orders are in the pipeline that day for any individual security on the platform (i.e.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In turn, if dark pool trades were publicly viewable in the same way, a retail shareholder could prevent loss by selling at the same time, before the price went any lower (assuming that shareholder is confident the price won't go back up).
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Because they are private and withheld from the public, in this way, they pose some risk for traders outside the dark pool.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Dark pools were largely motivated by the trades of large blocks and participants who did not want to move the market and cause front running.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] In the United States, however, these trades were stymied by Regulation NMS in 2004.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] However, under section 5 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 and Regulation ATS of 1998, off-exchange trading was allowed for up to five percent of the national volume of a stock.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] SEC adopted rules, as amendments to Regulation ATS, to require disclosures about dark pools in 2018.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] Known as Rule 304 of Regulation ATS, it requires the filing of Form ATS-N which includes a variety of disclosures including conflicts of interest, methods, fees, and so on.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] A review of these forms revealed a number of differences, including "tiering", "pegging", and "immediate-or-cancel (IOC)" orders, as well as a special features such as a speed bump by IEX to prevent high-frequency trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] FINRA reports data on ATS systems quarterly for free, which it began doing in July 2015.
[src:algorithmic-trading/dark-pool] When FINRA released this data, it showed that trades averaged 187 shares, which suggests that the pools were not used for large trades by institutional shareholders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] In finance, an **electronic trading platform**, also known as an **online trading platform**, is a computer software program that can be used to place orders for financial products over a network with a financial intermediary.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Various financial products can be traded by the trading platform, over a communication network with a financial intermediary or directly between the participants or members of the trading platform.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] This includes products such as stocks, bonds, currencies, commodities, derivatives and others, with a financial intermediary such as brokers, market makers, investment banks or stock exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Such platforms allow electronic trading to be carried out by users from any location and are in contrast to traditional floor trading using open outcry and telephone-based trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Sometimes the term trading platform is also used in reference to the trading software alone.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Electronic trading platforms typically stream live market prices on which users can trade and may provide additional trading tools, such as charting packages, news feeds and account management functions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Some platforms have been specifically designed to allow individuals to gain access to financial markets that could formerly only be accessed by specialist trading firms using direct market access.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] They may also be designed to automatically trade specific strategies based on technical analysis or to do high-frequency trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Electronic trading platforms are usually mobile-friendly and available for Windows, Mac, Linux, iOS and Android, making market entry easier and helping with the surge in retail investing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] The term "trading platform" is generally used to avoid confusion with "trading system".
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] The latter term usually refers to a trading method or strategy rather than the computer system used to execute orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] A platform is a type of computing system or operating environment such as a database or other specific software.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Financial transactions were handled manually by brokers or directly by counterparties until the 1970s.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] From then, electronic trading platforms were introduced.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] These platforms and trading venues included electronic communication networks, alternative trading systems and "dark pools".
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] The first electronic trading platforms were typically associated with stock exchanges and allowed brokers to place orders remotely using private dedicated networks and dumb terminals.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Early systems would not always provide live streaming prices and instead allowed brokers or clients to place an order which would be confirmed some time later; these were known as "request for quote" systems.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] In 1971, Nasdaq was created by the National Association of Securities Dealers and operated entirely electronically on a computer network.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] It rapidly gained popularity and by 1992, it accounted for 42% of trade volume in the US.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] With the advent of electronic financial markets, electronic trading platforms were also soon launched.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] In 1992, Globex became the first electronic trading platform to reach the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] E-Trade, a company that started as an online brokerage service, soon also launched its own platform aimed at the consumer.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] These platforms rapidly gained popularity with E-Trade's growth rate at 9% per month in 1999.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] In the late 2000s, with the emergence of digital tools, a new generation of investment companies started to appear, which began to offer services to assist non-professional investors in trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] In 2007, a multi-asset investment company, eToro, was founded, focusing on copy trading, social trading, and other types of trading services.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] In 2017, the bitcoin exchange Binance was founded.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Trading systems evolved to allow for live streaming prices and near instant execution of orders as well as using the internet as the underlying network meaning that location became much less relevant.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Some electronic trading platforms have built-in scripting tools and even APIs allowing traders to develop automatic or algorithmic trading systems and robots.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] The client graphical user interface of the electronic trading platforms could be used to place various orders and were also sometimes called trading turrets (though this may be a misuse of the term, as some refer to the specialized PBX phones used by traders).
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] During the period from 2001 to 2005, the development and proliferation of trading platforms saw the setting up of dedicated online trading portals, which were electronic online venues with a choice of many electronic trading platforms rather than being restricted to one institution's offering.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) promulgated Rule 17a-23, which required any registered automated trading platform to report information, including participants, orders, and trades every quarter.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Requiring platforms to comply with enhanced pre- and post-trade transparency requirements has provided a stronger incentive for users to trust electronic trading platforms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Market fragmentation led some Nasdaq market makers on Instinet to quote prices that were better than their own quotes on Nasdaq.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] To address this discrepancy, the SEC introduced the Order Handling Rules in 1996.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] These rules required stock exchange specialists and Nasdaq market makers to publicly display any price quoted on a proprietary trading system that represented an improvement of their displayed prices.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Another order handling rule required a market maker to display the size and price of any customer limit order that either increased size at the quoted price or improved the market maker's quotation.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Decimalization was instituted in 2001 by the SEC, requiring market makers to value financial instruments by increments of $0.01 as opposed to the previous standard of $0.0625.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] This change significantly lowered margins, providing an incentive for big dealers to utilize electronic management systems and eventually leading to lowered trading costs.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Electronic trading platforms frequently provide historical data, including graphs, to help their customers make trading decisions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] These diagrams may be expanded to contain a large number of dates and are frequently employed in technical analyses of particular instruments.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] To help consumers make decisions about their contracts, trading platforms frequently include recent news.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Articles on certain businesses may be included, as well as updated ratings provided by independent companies that focus on particular commodities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] Similar information to what professional traders can access is available to retail traders on different applications due to specialized news.
[src:algorithmic-trading/electronic-trading-platform] The user's portfolio can be tracked, which is another function that is frequently seen on trading platforms and can have an impact on trades based on a trader's past performance.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In 2016, HFT on average initiated 10–40% of trading volume in equities, and 10–15% of volume in foreign exchange and commodities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency traders move in and out of short-term positions at high volumes and high speeds aiming to capture sometimes a fraction of a cent in profit on every trade.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] HFT firms do not consume significant amounts of capital, accumulate positions or hold their portfolios overnight.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] As a result, HFT has a potential Sharpe ratio (a measure of reward to risk) tens of times higher than traditional buy-and-hold strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency traders typically compete against other HFTs, rather than long-term investors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] HFT firms compensate for low profit margins by executing extremely high volumes of trades, often numbering in the millions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] A substantial body of research argues that HFT and electronic trading pose new types of challenges to the financial system.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Algorithmic and high-frequency traders were both found to have contributed to volatility in the Flash Crash of May 6, 2010, when high-frequency liquidity providers rapidly withdrew from the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Several European countries have proposed curtailing or banning HFT due to concerns about volatility.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Other complaints against HFT include the argument that some HFT firms scrape profits from investors when index funds rebalance their portfolios.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The rapid-fire computer-based HFT developed gradually since 1983 after NASDAQ introduced a purely electronic form of trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] At the turn of the 21st century, HFT trades had an execution time of several seconds, whereas by 2010 this had decreased to milli- and even microseconds.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] At that time, high-frequency trading was still a little-known topic outside the financial sector, with an article published by the *New York Times* in July 2009 being one of the first to bring the subject to the public's attention.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] On September 2, 2013, Italy became the world's first country to introduce a tax specifically targeted at HFT, charging a levy of 0.02% on equity transactions lasting less than 0.5 seconds.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In the early 2000s, high-frequency trading still accounted for fewer than 10% of equity orders, but this proportion was soon to begin rapid growth.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] According to data from the NYSE, trading volume grew by about 164% between 2005 and 2009 for which high-frequency trading might be accounted.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The high-frequency strategy was first made popular by Renaissance Technologies who use both HFT and quantitative aspects in their trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Many high-frequency firms are market makers and provide liquidity to the market which lowers volatility and helps narrow bid–offer spreads, making trading and investing cheaper for other market participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In the United States in 2009, high-frequency trading firms represented 2% of the approximately 20,000 firms operating today, but accounted for 73% of all equity order volume.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The major U.S. high-frequency trading firms include Jane Street Capital , Hudson River Trading, Susquehanna International Group, XTX Markets, Virtu Financial, Tower Research Capital, IMC, Tradebot, Akuna Capital and Citadel LLC.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The Bank of England estimates similar percentages for the 2010 UK market share, also suggesting that in Europe HFT accounts for about 40% of equity orders volume and for Asia about 5–10%, with potential for rapid growth.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] By value, HFT was estimated in 2010 by consultancy *Tabb Group* to make up 56% of equity trades in the US and 38% in Europe.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] As HFT strategies become more widely used, it can be more difficult to deploy them profitably.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] According to an estimate from Frederi Viens of Purdue University, profits from HFT in the U.S. has been declining from an estimated peak of $5bn in 2009, to about $1.25bn in 2012.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Though the percentage of volume attributed to HFT has fallen in the equity markets, it has remained prevalent in the futures markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] According to a study in 2010 by Aite Group, about a quarter of major global futures volume came from professional high-frequency traders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In 2012, according to a study by the TABB Group, HFT accounted for more than 60 percent of all futures market volume in 2012 on U.S. exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency trading is quantitative trading that is characterized by short portfolio holding periods.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The success of high-frequency trading strategies is largely driven by their ability to simultaneously process large volumes of information, something ordinary human traders cannot do.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Specific algorithms are closely guarded by their owners.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Many practical algorithms are in fact quite simple arbitrages which could previously have been performed at lower frequency—competition tends to occur through who can execute them the fastest rather than who can create new breakthrough algorithms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The common types of high-frequency trading include several types of market-making, event arbitrage, statistical arbitrage, and latency arbitrage.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Most high-frequency trading strategies are not fraudulent, but instead exploit minute deviations from market equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] There can be a significant overlap between a "market maker" and "HFT firm".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] HFT firms characterize their business as "Market making" – a set of high-frequency trading strategies that involve placing a limit order to sell (or offer) or a buy limit order (or bid) in order to earn the bid-ask spread.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] By doing so, market makers provide a counterpart to incoming market orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Although the role of market maker was traditionally fulfilled by specialist firms, this class of strategy is now implemented by a large range of investors, thanks to wide adoption of direct market access.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Some high-frequency trading firms use market making as their primary strategy.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Automated Trading Desk (ATD), which was bought by Citigroup in July 2007, has been an active market maker, accounting for about 6% of total volume on both the NASDAQ and the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In May 2016, Citadel LLC bought assets of ATD from Citigroup.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Building up market making strategies typically involves precise modeling of the target market microstructure together with stochastic control techniques.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] These strategies appear intimately related to the entry of new electronic venues.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Academic study of Chi-X's entry into the European equity market reveals that its launch coincided with a large HFT that made markets using both the incumbent market, NYSE-Euronext, and the new market, Chi-X.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The study shows that the new market provided ideal conditions for HFT market-making, low fees (i.e., rebates for quotes that led to execution) and a fast system, yet the HFT was equally active in the incumbent market to offload nonzero positions.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] New market entry and HFT arrival are further shown to coincide with a significant improvement in liquidity supply.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Quote stuffing is a form of abusive market manipulation that has been employed by high-frequency traders (HFT) and is subject to disciplinary action.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] It involves quickly entering and withdrawing a large number of orders in an attempt to flood the market, creating confusion in the market and trading opportunities for high-frequency traders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Much information happens to be unwittingly embedded in market data, such as quotes and volumes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] By observing a flow of quotes, computers are capable of extracting information that has not yet crossed the news screens.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Since all quote and volume information is public, such strategies are fully compliant with all the applicable laws.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Filter trading is one of the more primitive high-frequency trading strategies that involves monitoring large amounts of stocks for significant or unusual price changes or volume activity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This includes trading on announcements, news, or other event criteria.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Software would then generate a buy or sell order depending on the nature of the event being looked for.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Tick trading often aims to recognize the beginnings of large orders being placed in the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] For example, a large order from a pension fund to buy will take place over several hours or even days, and will cause a rise in price due to increased demand.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] An arbitrageur can try to spot this happening, buy up the security, then profit from selling back to the pension fund.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This strategy has become more difficult since the introduction of dedicated trade execution companies in the 2000s which provide optimal trading for pension and other funds, specifically designed to remove the arbitrage opportunity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Another set of high-frequency trading strategies are strategies that exploit predictable temporary deviations from stable statistical relationships among securities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Statistical arbitrage at high frequencies is actively used in all liquid securities, including equities, bonds, futures, foreign exchange, etc.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency trading allows similar arbitrages using models of greater complexity involving many more than four securities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The TABB Group estimates that annual aggregate profits of high-frequency arbitrage strategies exceeded US$21 billion in 2009, although the Purdue study estimates the profits for all high frequency trading were US$5 billion in 2009.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Index arbitrage exploits index tracker funds which are bound to buy and sell large volumes of securities in proportion to their changing weights in indices.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] If a HFT firm is able to access and process information which predicts these changes before the tracker funds do so, they can buy up securities in advance of the trackers and sell them on to them at a profit.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Company news in electronic text format is available from many sources including commercial providers like *Bloomberg*, public news websites, and Twitter feeds.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Automated systems can identify company names, keywords and sometimes semantics to make news-based trades before human traders can process the news.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] A separate, "naïve" class of high-frequency trading strategies relies exclusively on ultra-low latency direct market access technology.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In these strategies, computer scientists rely on speed to gain minuscule advantages in arbitraging price discrepancies in some particular security trading simultaneously on disparate markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Another aspect of low latency strategy has been the switch from fiber optic to microwave and shortwave technology for long distance networking.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The switch to microwave transmission was because microwaves traveling in air suffer a less than 1% speed reduction compared to light traveling in a vacuum, whereas with conventional fiber optics light travels over 30% slower.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Especially since 2011, companies involved in HFT have massively invested in microwaves infrastructure to transmit data across key connections such as the one between New York City and Chicago but also between London and Frankfurt, going through Belgium thanks to a network of former US army antennas.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] However, microwave transmission requires line-of-sight propagation, which is difficult over long distances, driving some HFT firms to use shortwave radio instead.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Shortwave radio signals can be transmitted over a longer distance, but carry less information; in 2020, a hedge fund partner quoted in Bloomberg News said that shortwave bandwidth is insufficient for transmitting full order book feeds for low-latency strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Firms have also looked into using satellites to transmit market data.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency trading strategies may use properties derived from market data feeds to identify orders that are posted at sub-optimal prices.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Such orders may offer a profit to their counterparties that high-frequency traders can try to obtain.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Examples of these features include the age of an order or the sizes of displayed orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Tracking important order properties may also allow trading strategies to have a more accurate prediction of the future price of a security.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The effects of algorithmic and high-frequency trading are the subject of ongoing research.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High frequency trading causes regulatory concerns as a contributor to market fragility.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Regulators claim these practices contributed to volatility in the May 6, 2010, Flash Crash and find that risk controls are much less stringent for faster trades.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Members of the financial industry generally claim high-frequency trading substantially improves market liquidity, narrows bid–offer spread, lowers volatility and makes trading and investing cheaper for other market participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In September 2011, market data vendor Nanex LLC published a report stating the contrary.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] They looked at the amount of quote traffic compared to the value of trade transactions over 4 and half years and saw a 10-fold decrease in efficiency.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Nanex's owner is an outspoken detractor of high-frequency trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Many discussions about HFT focus solely on the frequency aspect of the algorithms and not on their decision-making logic (which is typically kept secret by the companies that develop them).
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This makes it difficult for observers to pre-identify market scenarios where HFT will dampen or amplify price fluctuations.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The growing quote traffic compared to trade value could indicate that more firms are trying to profit from cross-market arbitrage techniques that do not add significant value through increased liquidity when measured globally.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] More fully automated markets such as NASDAQ, Direct Edge, and BATS, in the US, gained market share from less automated markets such as the NYSE.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Economies of scale in electronic trading contributed to lowering commissions and trade processing fees, and contributed to international mergers and consolidation of financial exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The speeds of computer connections, measured in milliseconds or microseconds, have become important.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] For example, in 2009 the London Stock Exchange bought a technology firm called MillenniumIT and announced plans to implement its Millennium Exchange platform which they claim has an average latency of 126 microseconds.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This allows sub-millisecond resolution timestamping of the order book.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Off-the-shelf software currently allows for nanoseconds resolution of timestamps using a GPS clock with 100 nanoseconds precision.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Spending on computers and software in the financial industry increased to $26.4 billion in 2005.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The brief but dramatic stock market crash of May 6, 2010, was initially thought to have been caused by high-frequency trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged to its largest intraday point loss, but not percentage loss, in history, only to recover much of those losses within minutes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In the aftermath of the crash, several organizations argued that high-frequency trading was not to blame, and may even have been a major factor in minimizing and partially reversing the Flash Crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] CME Group, a large futures exchange, stated that, insofar as stock index futures traded on CME Group were concerned, its investigation had found no support for the notion that high-frequency trading was related to the crash, and actually stated it had a market stabilizing effect.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] However, after almost five months of investigations, the U.S.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The report found that the cause was a single sale of $4.1 billion in futures contracts by a mutual fund, identified as Waddell & Reed Financial, in an aggressive attempt to hedge its investment position.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] As prices in the futures market fell, there was a spillover into the equities markets where "the liquidity in the market evaporated because the automated systems used by most firms to keep pace with the market paused" and scaled back their trading or withdrew from the markets altogether.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] While some firms exited the market, high-frequency firms that remained in the market exacerbated price declines because they "'escalated their aggressive selling' during the downdraft".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In the years following the flash crash, academic researchers and experts from the CFTC pointed to high-frequency trading as just one component of the complex current U.S. market structure that led to the events of May 6, 2010.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The fastest technologies give traders an advantage over other "slower" investors as they can change prices of the securities they trade.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] According to author Walter Mattli, the ability of regulators to enforce the rules has greatly declined since 2005 with the passing of the Regulation National Market System (Reg NMS) by the SEC.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] As a result, the NYSE's quasi monopoly role as a stock rule maker was undermined and turned the stock exchange into one of many globally operating exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The market then became more fractured and granular, as did the regulatory bodies, and since stock exchanges had turned into entities also seeking to maximize profits, the one with the most lenient regulators were rewarded, and oversight over traders' activities was lost.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This fragmentation has greatly benefitted HFT.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency trading comprises many different types of algorithms.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Various studies reported that certain types of market-making high-frequency trading reduces volatility and does not pose a systemic risk, and lowers transaction costs for retail investors, without impacting long term investors.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Other studies, summarized in Aldridge, Krawciw, 2017 find that high-frequency trading strategies known as "aggressive" erode liquidity and cause volatility.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] High-frequency trading has been the subject of intense public focus and debate since the May 6, 2010, Flash Crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] At least one Nobel Prize–winning economist, Michael Spence, believes that HFT should be banned.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] A working paper found "the presence of high frequency trading has significantly mitigated the frequency and severity of end-of-day price dislocation".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In their joint report on the 2010 Flash Crash, the SEC and the CFTC stated that "market makers and other liquidity providers widened their quote spreads, others reduced offered liquidity, and a significant number withdrew completely from the markets" during the flash crash.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Politicians, regulators, scholars, journalists and market participants have all raised concerns on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This has led to discussion of whether high-frequency market makers should be subject to various kinds of regulations.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In a September 22, 2010, speech, SEC chairperson Mary Schapiro signaled that US authorities were considering the introduction of regulations targeted at HFT.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] She said, "high frequency trading firms have a tremendous capacity to affect the stability and integrity of the equity markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] A later SEC chair Mary Jo White pushed back against claims that high-frequency traders have an inherent benefit in the markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] SEC associate director Gregg Berman suggested that the current debate over HFT lacks perspective.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In an April 2014 speech, Berman argued: "It's much more than just the automation of quotes and cancels, in spite of the seemingly exclusive fixation on this topic by much of the media and various outspoken market pundits.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The Chicago Federal Reserve letter of October 2012, titled "How to keep markets safe in an era of high-speed trading", reports on the results of a survey of several dozen financial industry professionals including traders, brokers, and exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Exchanges offered a type of order called a "Flash" order (on NASDAQ, it was called "Bolt" on the Bats stock exchange) that allowed an order to lock the market (post at the same price as an order on the other side of the order book) for a small amount of time (5 milliseconds).
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This order type was available to all participants but since HFT's adapted to the changes in market structure more quickly than others, they were able to use it to "jump the queue" and place their orders before other order types were allowed to trade at the given price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Currently, the majority of exchanges do not offer flash trading, or have discontinued it.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] By March 2011, the NASDAQ, BATS, and Direct Edge exchanges had all ceased offering its Competition for Price Improvement functionality (widely referred to as "flash technology/trading").
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In March 2012, regulators fined Octeg LLC, the equities market-making unit of high-frequency trading firm Getco LLC, for $450,000.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Octeg violated Nasdaq rules and failed to maintain proper supervision over its stock trading activities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The fine resulted from a request by Nasdaq OMX for regulators to investigate the activity at Octeg LLC from the day after the May 6, 2010, Flash Crash through the following December.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Nasdaq determined the Getco subsidiary lacked reasonable oversight of its algo-driven high-frequency trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In October 2013, regulators fined Knight Capital $12 million for the trading malfunction that led to its collapse.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Knight was found to have violated the SEC's market access rule, in effect since 2010 to prevent such mistakes.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Regulators stated the HFT firm ignored dozens of error messages before its computers sent millions of unintended orders to the market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Knight Capital eventually merged with Getco to form KCG Holdings.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Knight lost over $460 million from its trading errors in August 2012 that caused disturbance in the U.S. stock market.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In September 2014, HFT firm Latour Trading LLC agreed to pay a SEC penalty of $16 million.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Latour is a subsidiary of New York-based high-frequency trader Tower Research Capital LLC.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] According to the SEC's order, for at least two years Latour underestimated the amount of risk it was taking on with its trading activities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] By using faulty calculations, Latour managed to buy and sell stocks without holding enough capital.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] At times, the Tower Research Capital subsidiary accounted for 9% of all U.S. stock trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The SEC noted the case is the largest penalty for a violation of the net capital rule.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In response to increased regulation, such as by FINRA, some have argued that instead of promoting government intervention, it would be more efficient to focus on a solution that mitigates information asymmetries among traders and their backers; others argue that regulation does not go far enough.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In 2018, the European Union introduced the MiFID II/MiFIR regulation.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] On January 12, 2015, the SEC announced a $14 million penalty against a subsidiary of BATS Global Markets, an exchange operator that was founded by high-frequency traders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The BATS subsidiary Direct Edge failed to properly disclose order types on its two exchanges EDGA and EDGX.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] These exchanges offered three variations of controversial "Hide Not Slide" orders and failed to accurately describe their priority to other orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The SEC found the exchanges disclosed complete and accurate information about the order types "only to some members, including certain high-frequency trading firms that provided input about how the orders would operate".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The complaint was made in 2011 by Haim Bodek.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Reported in January 2015, UBS agreed to pay $14.4 million to settle charges of not disclosing an order type that allowed high-frequency traders to jump ahead of other participants.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The SEC stated that UBS failed to properly disclose to all subscribers of its dark pool "the existence of an order type that it pitched almost exclusively to market makers and high-frequency trading firms".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] UBS broke the law by accepting and ranking hundreds of millions of orders priced in increments of less than one cent, which is prohibited under Regulation NMS.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The order type called PrimaryPegPlus enabled HFT firms "to place sub-penny-priced orders that jumped ahead of other orders submitted at legal, whole-penny prices".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In June 2014, high-frequency trading firm Citadel LLC was fined $800,000 for violations that included quote stuffing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Nasdaq's disciplinary action stated that Citadel "failed to prevent the strategy from sending millions of orders to the exchanges with few or no executions".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] It was pointed out that Citadel "sent multiple, periodic bursts of order messages, at 10,000 orders per second, to the exchanges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In July 2013, it was reported that Panther Energy Trading LLC was ordered to pay $4.5 million to U.S. and U.K. regulators on charges that the firm's high-frequency trading activities manipulated commodity markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Panther's computer algorithms placed and quickly canceled bids and offers in futures contracts including oil, metals, interest rates and foreign currencies, the U.S.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Commodity Futures Trading Commission said.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In October 2014, Panther's sole owner Michael Coscia was charged with six counts of commodities fraud and six counts of "spoofing".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The indictment stated that Coscia devised a high-frequency trading strategy to create a false impression of the available liquidity in the market, "and to fraudulently induce other market participants to react to the deceptive market information he created".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In November 7, 2019, it was reported that Tower Research was ordered to pay $67.4 million in fines to the CFTC to settle allegations that three former traders at the firm engaged in spoofing from at least March 2012 through December 2013.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The New York-based firm entered into a deferred prosecution agreement with the Justice Department.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In October 2014, Athena Capital Research LLC was fined $1 million on price manipulation charges.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The high-speed trading firm used $40 million to rig prices of thousands of stocks, including eBay, according to U.S. regulators.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The HFT firm Athena manipulated closing prices commonly used to track stock performance with "high-powered computers, complex algorithms and rapid-fire trades", the SEC said.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The regulatory action is one of the first market manipulation cases against a firm engaged in high-frequency trading.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Reporting by Bloomberg noted the HFT industry is "besieged by accusations that it cheats slower investors".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In January 2023, Citadel Securities was fined ₩11.88 billion ($9.66 million) by the Financial Services Commission of South Korea for distorting stock prices with the use of immediate-or-cancel orders and by filling gaps in bid prices.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In July 2020, Citadel Securities was fined $700,000 by FINRA for trading ahead of customer orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Advanced computerized trading platforms and market gateways are becoming standard tools of most types of traders, including high-frequency traders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Broker-dealers now compete on routing order flow directly, in the fastest and most efficient manner, to the line handler where it undergoes a strict set of risk filters before hitting the execution venue(s).
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Ultra-low latency direct market access (ULLDMA) is a hot topic amongst brokers and technology vendors such as Goldman Sachs, Credit Suisse, and UBS.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Typically, ULLDMA systems can currently handle high amounts of volume and boast round-trip order execution speeds (from hitting "transmit order" to receiving an acknowledgment) of 10 milliseconds or less.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Such performance is achieved with the use of hardware acceleration or even full-hardware processing of incoming market data, in association with high-speed communication protocols, such as 10 Gigabit Ethernet or PCI Express.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] More specifically, some companies provide full-hardware appliances based on FPGA technology to obtain sub-microsecond end-to-end market data processing.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Buy side traders made efforts to curb predatory HFT strategies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Brad Katsuyama, co-founder of the IEX, led a team that implemented THOR, a securities order-management system that splits large orders into smaller sub-orders that arrive at the same time to all the exchanges through the use of intentional delays.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] This largely prevents information leakage in the propagation of orders that high-speed traders can take advantage of.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In 2016, after having Intercontinental Exchange Inc. and others fail to prevent SEC approval of IEX's launch and having failed to sue as it had threatened to do over the SEC approval, Nasdaq launched a "speed bump" product of its own to compete with IEX.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] According to Nasdaq CEO Robert Greifeld "the regulator shouldn't have approved IEX without changing the rules that required quotes to be immediately visible".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The IEX speed bump—or trading slowdown—is 350 microseconds, which the SEC ruled was within the "immediately visible" parameter.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] The slowdown promises to impede HST ability "often [to] cancel dozens of orders for every trade they make".
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Outside of US equities, several notable spot foreign exchange (FX) trading platforms—including ParFX, EBS Market, and Refinitiv FXall—have implemented their own "speed bumps" to curb or otherwise limit HFT activity.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] Unlike the IEX fixed length delay that retains the temporal ordering of messages as they are received by the platform, the spot FX platforms' speed bumps reorder messages so the first message received is not necessarily that processed for matching first.
[src:algorithmic-trading/high-frequency-trading] In short, the spot FX platforms' speed bumps seek to reduce the benefit of a participant being faster than others, as has been described in various academic papers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Securities and Exchange Commission defines a "market maker" as a firm that stands ready to buy and sell stock on a regular and continuous basis at a publicly quoted price.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] A Designated Primary Market Maker (DPM) is a specialized market maker approved by an exchange to guarantee a buy or sell position in a particular assigned security, option, or option index.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Most foreign exchange trading firms are market makers, as are many banks.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] The foreign exchange market maker both buys foreign currency from clients and sells it to other clients.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] They derive income from the trading price differentials, helping the market by providing liquidity, reducing transaction costs, and facilitating trade.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Market makers that stand ready to buy and sell stocks listed on an exchange, such as the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) or the London Stock Exchange (LSE), are called "third market makers".
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Most stock exchanges operate on a "matched bargain" or "order driven" basis.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] When a buyer's bid price meets a seller's offer price or vice versa, the stock exchange's matching system decides that a deal has been executed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] In such a system, there may be no designated or official market makers, but market makers nevertheless exist.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] As of October 2008, there were over two thousand market makers in the United States, and over one hundred in Canada.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] In the United States, the NYSE and NYSE American, among others, have designated market makers, formerly known as "specialists", who act as the official market maker for a given security.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] The market makers provide a required amount of liquidity to the security's market, and take the other side of trades when there are short-term buy-and-sell-side imbalances in customer orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] In return, the specialist is granted various informational and trade execution advantages.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Other U.S. exchanges, most prominently the NASDAQ stock exchange, employ several competing official market makers in a security.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] These market makers are required to maintain two-sided markets during exchange hours and are obligated to buy and sell at their displayed bids and offers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] They typically do not receive the trading advantages a specialist does, but they do get some, such as the ability to naked short a stock, i.e., selling it without borrowing it.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] In most situations, only official market makers are permitted to engage in naked shorting.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Changes to the rules in the 2000s and 2010s have explicitly banned naked shorting by options market makers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] In liquid markets like the NYSE, nearly every asset has open interest, providing two benefits: price takers can buy or sell at any time, and observers can continually monitor a precise price of every asset.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] A prediction market, or market explicitly designed to uncover the value of an asset, relies heavily on continual price discovery holding true.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Prediction markets benefit from automated market makers, or algorithmic traders that maintain constant open interest, providing needed liquidity to the markets that would be difficult to provide naturally.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Examples of New York market makers are Optiver, Jane Street Capital, Flow Traders, IMC, and Virtu Financial, according to Article 17(13) of Regulation (EU) No 236/2012 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 14 March 2012.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] On the LSE, there are official market makers for many securities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Some of the LSE's member firms take on the obligation of always making a two-way price in each of the stocks in which they make markets.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Their prices are the ones displayed on the Stock Exchange Automated Quotation (SEAQ) system and it is they who generally deal with brokers buying or selling stock on behalf of clients.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Proponents of the official market making system claim market makers add to the liquidity and depth of the market by taking a short or long position for a time, thus assuming some risk in return for the chance of a small profit.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] On the LSE, one can always buy and sell stock: each stock always has at least two market makers and they are obliged to deal.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] In contrast, on smaller, order-driven markets such as the JSE Securities Exchange it can be difficult to determine the buying and selling prices of even a small block of stocks that lack a clear and immediate market value because there are often no buyers or sellers on the order board.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Unofficial market makers are free to operate on order driven markets or, indeed, on the LSE.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] They do not have the obligation to always be making a two-way price, but they do not have the advantage that everyone must deal with them either.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Examples of UK Market makers since Big Bang Day are Peel Hunt LLP, Winterflood Securities, Liberum Capital, Shore Capital, Fairfax IS and Altium Securities.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Prior to the Big Bang, jobbers had exclusive rights of market making on the LSE.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] The Frankfurt Stock Exchange (FWB) runs a system of market makers appointed by the listed companies.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Designated Sponsors secure higher liquidity by quoting binding prices for buying and selling the shares.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] The largest market maker by number of mandates in Germany is ODDO BHF Corporates & Markets AG.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Since 2018, the Tokyo Stock Exchange has had an ETF Market Making Incentive Scheme in place, which provides incentives to designated market makers who maintain quoting obligations in qualified ETFs.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] This list of market makers includes Nomura Securities, Flow Traders, and Optiver.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Liquidity provision in a decentralized network protocol, such as the trading or transacting of a cryptocurrency on an exchange, works rather differently.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Decentralized markets by definition do not have official market makers, and there are no regulations enforced by centralized entities involved at the protocol level.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Companies or individuals may become market makers by simply using or trading the protocol at high volumes and by providing liquidity to the protocol, typically in return for the prospect of making an ROI on the assets committed to the liquidity pools.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Decentralized exchanges offer trading discounts for high-volume traders in order to encourage companies and individuals to provide liquidity as unofficial market makers.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Decentralized markets fall outside of the regulatory reach of traditional courts with jurisdiction in defined geographic boundaries.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Therefore governments may have difficulty auditing, regulating or shutting down such protocols since the protocols have no central or headquarters jurisdiction in which they operate.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] The network operates on the principles, and according to the code, that is running on the network.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] The income of a market maker is the difference between the bid price, the price at which the firm is willing to buy a stock, and the ask price, the price at which the firm is willing to sell it.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] It is known as the market-maker spread, or bid–ask spread.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Supposing that equal numbers of buy and sell orders arrive and the price never changes, this is the amount that the market maker will gain on each round trip.
[src:algorithmic-trading/market-maker] Market makers usually also provide liquidity to the firm's clients, for which they earn a commission.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] An **order book** is the list of orders (manual or electronic) that a trading venue (in particular stock exchanges) uses to record the interest of buyers and sellers in a particular financial instrument.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] A matching engine uses the book to determine which orders can be fully or partially executed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] In securities trading, an order book contains the list of buy orders and the list of sell orders.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] For each entry it must keep among others, some means of identifying the party (even if this identification is obscured, as in a dark pool), the number of securities and the price that the buyer or seller are bidding/asking for the particular security.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] When several orders contain the same price, they are referred to as being on a price level.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] Practically, this means that if a bid comes at that price level, all the sell orders on that price level could potentially fulfill that.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] When the order book is part of a matching engine, orders are matched as the interest of buyers and sellers can be satisfied.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] When there are orders where the bid price is equal or higher than the lowest ask, those orders can be immediately fulfilled and will not be part of the open orders book.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] If this situation remains, due to an error or a condition of the market, the order book is said to be crossed.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] The highest bid and the lowest ask are referred to as the top of the book.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] They are interesting because they signal the prevalent market and the bid and ask price that would be needed to get an order fulfilled.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] The difference between the highest bid and the lowest ask is called the bid–ask spread.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] The book depth refers simply to the number of price levels available at a particular time in the book.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] Sometimes the book is represented to a fixed depth, and orders beyond that depth are ignored or rejected, and in other cases the book can contain unlimited levels.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] In most practical applications, an order book contains bid and offer for one security, contract or good, with a specialist matching orders for the specific item.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] In his work, Jean-François Mertens extends this and constructs an order matching mechanism that works across specialists, where he can cross orders that are not only in terms of bid and offer for a given traded item, but bids and offer can be expressed as a linear function of other traded items.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] The advent of retail trading software in the early 2000s enabled more complex charting options for what was previously numerical data.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] An order book might also refer to a business's list of open, unshipped, customer orders, normally time-phased and valued at actual individual order prices, that may include margin and profitability analysis.
[src:algorithmic-trading/order-book] The basic principle of the order book as used in financial securities, when used to gauge supply and demand, can also apply to the trade of other goods (for example e-commerce).
